+---
+aliases:
+  - shared notifications capability (router + email + slack)
+status: idea
+created: 2026-05-16
+---
+# Spec [[cat003]] [[board]]
+
+## problem
+
+Three internal services (`auth`, `metrics`, `reports`) each maintain
+their own ad-hoc notification path: smtplib snippets in `metrics` and
+`reports`, and a `mail` shell-out in `auth`. There is no shared
+notifications building block today — `feature-read` surfaced only
+[[ft001]] (basic-auth) and [[ft002]] (vault-secrets), so the dedup
+check passes and a fresh `ft###` is warranted. Slack alerts are now
+also requested, and the metrics team flags pager-style SMS as
+plausible after-hours work. The status quo of pasting transport
+snippets per service will compound with every new channel.
+
+**Capability boundary.** The proposal is a horizontal notifications
+capability with **three atomic `ft###` candidates** (granularity
+check, per the `ft###` single-`providing` / single-`api_surface` /
+single-`status` schema). All three are minted at spec-writing time;
+none are pre-minted by this idea card:
+
+- **ft-notifications-router** — typed-message dispatch surface. One
+  `send(notification)` API that fan-outs to one or more channel
+  adapters; carries the templating, retry, and dedup policy that
+  channels inherit.
+- **ft-email-send** — email channel adapter (internal MTA via
+  smtplib, no external relay). Replaces today's three copy/paste
+  smtplib paths.
+- **ft-slack-send** — slack channel adapter (webhook-based). Net-new
+  consumer for metrics-team alerts.
+
+**Plausible-later (NOT in this spec):** `ft-sms-send` — captured as
+intent, deliberately deferred. SMS has no committed consumer beyond
+"metrics team wants pager-style after-hours" and adds a paid-vendor
+dependency. Mint when a real consumer story lands; YAGNI ruthlessly.
+
+**Sizing rationale (one `sp###`, three `ft###`).** Per the idea-feature
+sizing rule (step 8): three capabilities, small scaffolding of
+well-understood shapes (smtplib wrapper, slack webhook POST, dispatcher
+with a channel registry), three small internal-service consumers, no
+independent ship windows demanded. Splitting at task level during
+`spec-refinement` is cheaper than splitting at `sp###` level here. If
+spec-writing discovers any of the three is non-trivial (e.g. retry
+semantics need their own ADR), promote that one to its own sp### at
+that point.
+
+**Consumers (via `implementation-read` survey).** No existing
+`im###` carries notification logic today — [[im001]] (reports
+dashboard) consumes [[ft001]] only, and `auth` / `metrics` have no
+`im###` cards yet. The three ad-hoc paths live directly in service
+code:
+
+- `src/services/auth/` — welcome-email path, currently shells out
+  to `mail`. Migration target.
+- `src/services/metrics/` — alert path, currently stdout +
+  ad-hoc smtplib. Migration target; will gain slack as a
+  net-new channel.
+- `src/services/reports/` — report-ready email, currently
+  smtplib. Migration target.
+
+Each migration is a thin call-site swap once the router is in place.
+
+**Category.** [[cat003|infrastructure]] — cross-service plumbing.
+The feature itself is transport plumbing; observability ([[cat004]])
+applies to the metrics consumer but is not where the capability
+lives. [[cat001|security]] is reachable via secret retrieval but
+that's already covered by [[ft002|vault-secrets]] — the router
+consumes vault, no security category needed on the feature itself.
+[[cat002|data]] does not apply (no persistent state intended; see
+constraints below).
+
+**Binding / conflicting ADRs.**
+
+- [[adr0003]] *(No external SMTP relay — services use smtplib
+  directly)* — **conflicts directly with this proposal**. The ADR
+  consequence "three copy/paste smtplib snippets across services" is
+  exactly the smell driving this spec. Resolution path at
+  spec-writing: file a new ADR superseding [[adr0003]] with
+  decision "email transport consolidated behind
+  `ft-notifications-router` + `ft-email-send`; smtplib stays the
+  on-host SMTP client, but call-sites move behind the router."
+  Flagging here so spec-writing does not silently violate the
+  existing decision.
+- [[adr0001]] *(All services authenticate via ft001 basic-auth)* —
+  out of scope; notification surfaces are internal callers, no
+  auth-decision delta.
+- [[adr0002]] *(Reports written to Postgres, retained 90 days)* —
+  out of scope; this capability does not persist message bodies.
+
+**Constraints inherited.** From [[cat003]]: cross-service plumbing
+must be reusable and not service-specific. From the
+non-application of [[cat002]]: this capability is intentionally
+stateless (no message store, no audit trail in v1) — if audit/log of
+sent notifications becomes a requirement, it's a follow-up `ft###`,
+not a widening of these three.
+
+**Migration sketch (one line per ad-hoc path).**
+
+- `auth` welcome email — replace `mail` shell-out with
+  `router.send(WelcomeEmail(user))`. Net deletion of ~20 lines.
+- `metrics` alert path — replace stdout + smtplib with
+  `router.send(MetricsAlert(...))`; gains slack target via channel
+  config without code change in metrics. Net deletion of ~30 lines.
+- `reports` ready-email — replace smtplib with
+  `router.send(ReportReady(run_id))`. Net deletion of ~25 lines.
+
+**Open questions deferred to spec-writing.**
+
+- Retry / dedup policy: at router level or per-channel?
+- Template registry: in-tree YAML vs Python dataclass per
+  notification type?
+- Slack channel mapping (per-notification-type → channel name) —
+  configuration source?
+
+These are spec-stage decisions, not idea-stage.
+
+---
